INSERT INTO wp_comments VALUES ("6","4909","Sybil Alvarado","sybil.alvarado@att.net","","108.222.63.107","2018-07-27 12:43:50","2018-07-27 12:43:50","How proud you make a \"mama\"   I didn\'t know you climbed those tall pine trees!!!!!
Love you Rob for all you were and are!!!!!","0","1","Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/64.0.3282.140 Safari/537.36 Edge/17.17134","","0","0"),
("7","4933","Kenneth W Hill","kwhill2012@gmail.com","","107.130.156.251","2018-08-31 18:36:18","2018-08-31 18:36:18","Some of the memories Robert had I have not thought of in decades. Catching chicken chokers...just use a lenght of grass and stick one end down the hole it has made and then draw the grass out slowly and the grub most times would be holding on...then I was use them for fish bait in the pond beside our dairy.
I started Benton school in 1955-56 school year, a year before most of you.

Grade school was fun for I loved going out and playing dodgeball or red rover. Marbles was not that much fun...School was hard for me. Reading was especially hard, as letter swam and changed shape on the page as I tried to read. During my junior year,  I finally learned I wasn\'t alone; other people had the same problem reading I have...dyslexia. To this day, reading is still difficult for me. Numbers on the other hand, always made sense.
Assembly in the auditorium was fun as we got to go over where the big kids where.
Robert was very fast and I remember one day out training the coach had me and him pair up for a quick 220 challenge...I had Robert for a short distance but then he pulled ahead and beat me by a nose. That was fun...

 College was good and being at the LSU main campus you got to see many Tiger games: football, basketball, etc. I still hated English.



I remember one senoir class pulled a prank over a long weekend by letting loose several pigs in the high school...I was glad I was not in those grades yet.
Hard work hauling hay paid the bills and put us kids thru college. Moving 1800 to 2000 bales a day in this heat, boy I do not see how we got it done. Also each bale weighed from 60 to 75 pounds. 
Family:
 I married fellow Benton Tiger Sandra Pemberton (Class of 1968) in 1971. Although the marriage only lasted a few short years, Sandra and I were blessed  with two beautiful little girls – Tammy and Carmen. Today. Tammy is a nurse.  She and her husband Larry live northeast of Dallas on Lake Tawakoni. They have two grown children of their own. Christopher and Brianna (Bree). Last Christmas, Christopher became engage to his long time girlfriend Paige Buchanan. They live in the Denver area where Chris is pursuing a career in coaching. Bree lives in Lewisville, and works as a veterinary surgical tech while trying to get into veterinary school.
My other daughter, Carmen, lives outside of Seattle on Kitsap Peninsula. She is the mother of four grown children: Haley (my first and shortest grandchild), Sean, Robert and Brandon.  Brandon graduated high school this past June.  Robert is the father of my first great-grandchild Pressley a beautiful little girl who\'s almost 2.
Sadly, I must report the mother of my children, passed away six years ago.
Both of my parents, Walter and Dorothy, have passed away. My brother, Glen, lives in Cotton Valley with his wife, Jane. Glen has two children and several grandchildren. He claims he will retire this fall. My sister, Sharon, retired from teaching in Arlington Texas several years ago. She and her husband George now make their home in the mountains of Colorado in the picturesque town of Buena Vista.  She has two sons and two grandsons.

Education: I started at LSU in Baton Rouge but finish my BA at the Shreveport campus. I also have a MBA from Amber U. in Garland Texas. At the time of my retirement from AAFES (Army and Air Force Exchange) I was certified as an Equal Employment Opportunity (EEO) investigator and Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR) mediator. 
Career: I started with Skyline trailors off of Swain Lake Road. Then went to West and Co. (Gibson\'s), then Montgomery Wards, then Western Electric, then Eckerd Drugs and finally AAFES. I retired in Dec 2012 from AAFES with 25 plus years of service.
We currently live on Richland Chambers lake, and I mean right on the lake, with views of the water that is perfect any day we are out by the shore.
Health is very good now. I\'m using a Bipap machine that has improved my sleeping greatly. Without it I might not be here today. Then last year I had heart surgery which corrected several nerve bundles that where firing out of sink with the rest of my heart.
Memories: One that comes to mind in my early years is that all grades where in the red brick high school as we knew it. Playing throw back football at recess was a very rough game, many of us came home with clothes torn up. Later years Robert A., Mike DeMoss, Hal and several others would get together for either a chess or a monopoly tournament, these where fun. A favorite memory I have from high school has to be about my Dad. I would go with him out to a deer camp towards Bellevue to play poker with a bunch of older men. A dinner would be cooked to be either BBQ or deep fried fish or deer along with plenty of cold drinks, I would have a beer once in awhile. Two other memories that hold a special place with me are (1) playing a basketball games against the faculty and (2) playing a pickup volly ball match with Coach Newman. I remember one such match in I was paired opposite him across net and I went up to block his return and I did, but the ball caught me right between the eyes and then landed inside his court and so I won the point, ouch...Do you remember the fad of yo-yo\'s, those were fun trying to do many of the tricks I could see being done on tv...Also, hola hoops even to this day I cannot keep them going...One memory that was fun was going to the soda shop in town and having a Pepsi and dropping salted peanuts into it and then drinking this mixture, all while reading comic books. One year, not sure which, our class got together to help a charity drive by asking for donations from drivers going up and down Benton road, do not remember how much we collected but I do remember it was more than what had ever been collected before from Benton.
Basketball was my go to sport in high school. I was okay and enjoyed playing even later in life. I had one AAFES assignment to the Azores for two years and during our stay I would go to the gym and get in a pickup game with some of military men station there. It was a challenge as I was playing against kids half my age, me being 40+ and they being 20+. It was a lot of fun, I learned that I could still keep up with them and after getting in shape I could still flat footed jump and grab the rim. I also played in the over 30 league while in the Azores.    
Over the years since high school I have learned to play pool, golf, darts and backgammon. Of these backgammon was my favorite. Now I love playing board games like: Ticket to Ride, Stone Age, Power Grid and many other games that I cannot recall. Kevin and I go to a board game conventions here in Dalles and do nothing but play board games of various genrie types. These conventions last for four to five days and we play different types of games for 10 to 12 hours each day. I love going to play but the biggest joy I get is seeing and talking with people that come to the convention from all over the world, New Zealand and Isarel being the furtherest. My current obsession with game playing is a computor based game in which I play against the AI, with a game called CIVILIZATION by Sid Meier.  
My biggest passion right now is deer hunting, no surprise here as I have been doing that since I was about 8. I have a place in OK of about 240 acres with a 16x28 foot cabin having almost all the necessities needed to stay in the woods for at least a week. If we need more then town in just 30 minutes down the road. Us, \'we\' Tammy does not let me go by myself so I always have a partner with me while I\'m there.
 I spend most of  my time watching reality shows: Alone, Mountain Men, Jeapordy, Who wants to be a Millonaire, Chopped, almost any cooking show, HGTV (love FLEA MARKET FLIP) and ANW. When we want to get out we love going to antique stores or flea markets that are within close driving distance.","0","0","Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/68.0.3440.106 Safari/537.36","","0","0"),
("8","4909","Roger Johnson","roger@northshreve.com","http://www.northshreve.com","12.189.47.242","2018-09-01 15:51:51","2018-09-01 15:51:51","Many years ago we agreed to share our story since High School and you did, a little late but you did!!!  Wonderful story and life.  God has blessed you and based on the person I knew in High School it is deserved.","0","1","Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/64.0.3282.140 Safari/537.36 Edge/17.17134","","0","0"),
("9","4943","Rob\'s Mom","sybil.alvarado@att.net","","108.222.63.107","2018-09-04 15:56:11","2018-09-04 15:56:11","Your faith is inspiring Roger, thank you for your story!!!!","0","1","Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; WOW64; rv:61.0) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/61.0","","0","0"),
("10","5017","Janis Martin Smith","jquiltfabrics@outlook.com","","97.43.64.211","2018-09-21 03:55:28","2018-09-21 03:55:28","I have this very vivid memory of Gary Martin.  He was such a gorgeous young man.  Both of us being \"Martin\'s\",  we walked together during graduation.  Boy !! did we have a good time. When we sit down, the chatter started.  We were wondering if we were going to actually get a diploma.  My grades weren\'t anything to brag about and I seriously doubt that his was either.  So we marched up and received this gigantic SEALED envelope.  Sealed, licked tight with glue.  I couldn\'t believe this was a silly thick, padded envelope.  I wanted just one piece of paper.  Instantly knowing that there was no diploma in it.  I bravely smiled like a gracious \'married lady\' and marched back to my seat where Gary was ripping into his sealed envelope.  We kinda fell into each other laughing with joy ( and relief) that we got our \'piece of paper\'.  We had the world by the tail.  I know ya\'ll were all around us.  But my world was wrapped around Gary and two \' pieces of paper\'.  Whatever else happened that night, I do not remember.

By the way, I got married about 5 weeks before we graduated so I thought I was really something.  Married, graduated and ready to take on the world. I am  just sorry that Gary can\'t celebrate with us.","0","0","Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/69.0.3497.100 Safari/537.36","","0","0"),
("11","4579","Kenneth Hill","kwhill2012@gmail.com","","107.130.156.251","2018-09-25 16:45:15","2018-09-25 16:45:15","Some of the memories Robert had I have not thought of in decades. Catching chicken chokers...just use a lenght of grass and stick one end down the hole it has made and then draw the grass out slowly and the grub most times would be holding on...then I was use them for fish bait in the pond beside our dairy.
I started Benton school in 1955-56 school year, a year before most of you. Rheumatic fever, held me back a year, so by second grade y\'all caught up with me.
Grade school was fun. I loved going out and playing dodgeball, crack the whip and  red rover. I didn\'t enjoy playing marbles... While I liked recess and the play ground, the classroom was torture for me. Reading was especially hard. Letter swam  across the page. They  changed shape and size as I tried to read. Books never  voluntarily revealed their contents to me. Everytime I opened a book or turned a page, I was in a fight. During my junior year,  I finally learned I wasn\'t alone; other people had the same problem reading I have...dyslexia. To this day, reading is still difficult for me. Numbers on the other hand, always made sense.
Assembly in the auditorium was fun as we got to go over where the big kids where.
Robert was very fast and I remember one day out training the coach had me and him pair up for a quick 220 challenge...I had Robert for a short distance but then he pulled ahead and beat me by a nose. That was fun...
 College was good and being at the LSU main campus you got to see many Tiger games: football, basketball, etc. I still hated English.
I remember one senior class pulled a prank over a long weekend by letting loose several pigs in the high school...I was glad I was not in those grades yet.
Hard work hauling hay paid the bills and put us kids thru college. Moving 1800 to 2000 bales a day in the heat, boy I do not see how we got it done. Also each bale weighed from 60 to 75 pounds. 
Family:
 I married fellow Benton Tiger Sandra Pemberton (Class of 1968) in 1971. Although the marriage only lasted a few short years, Sandra and I were blessed  with two beautiful little girls – Tammy and Carmen. Today. Tammy is a nurse.  She and her husband Larry live northeast of Dallas on Lake Tawakoni. They have two grown children of their own. Christopher and Brianna (Bree). Last Christmas, Christopher became engage to his long time girlfriend Paige Buchanan. They live in the Denver area where Chris is pursuing a career in coaching. Bree lives in Lewisville, and works as a veterinary surgical tech while trying to get into veterinary school.
My other daughter, Carmen, lives outside of Seattle on Kitsap Peninsula. She is the mother of four grown children: Haley (my first and shortest grandchild), Sean, Robert and Brandon.  Brandon graduated high school this past June.  Robert is the father of my first great-grandchild Pressley a beautiful little girl who\'s almost 2.
Sadly, I must report the mother of my children, passed away six years ago.

In 1983, while working for Eckerd Drugs, I transferred to Dallas. A few months later I met a pretty, young divorced mother of two. Little did I know I would still be spending most of my time with her 34 years later. Tammy and I married in April 1985. Her two children quickly became OUR two children. Our son Kevin, does something with computers that neither Tammy nor I quite understand. He and his wife, Amanda live in Keller, just north of Fort Worth, with their two sons Brandon (yes. we have two grandsons name Brandon) age 6 and Ryan (age 3). Please note the 23 year age difference between my oldest grandchild and my youngest.
Our youngest daughter, Sarah and her husband Randy make the Denver area their home. Although, she lives a bike ride away from downtown Denver, she\'s our farmer child. She raises chickens in her backyard (no cows). She also plants a garden every spring. Sarah is  a former band and choir teacher. Her husband  works in the field of cybersecurity.  These two are our world travellers and adventure seekers. It must be the thin mountain air.
Tammy and I made Arlington, TX our home 24 years, but last year we made a change. We purchased a house on the banks of Richland Chambers Lake which is a little over an hour\'s drive south east of Dallas, and about 15 minutes east of Corsicana. After so many years in the hectic metroplex, we enjoy the quiet, the slower pace of life, and the daily communion with nature we rediscovered here at the lake. What they say really is true...There\'s no bad day at the lake.
My brother, Glen, lives in Cotton Valley with his wife, Jan. Glen has two children and several grandchildren. He claims he will retire this fall. My sister, Sharon, retired from teaching in Arlington Texas several years ago. She and her husband George now make their home in the mountains of Colorado in the picturesque town of Buena Vista.  She has two sons and two grandsons.
Sadly, both of my parents have passed away.  Dad or Waldo, as he came to be known, died just last year.
Education:
 I started at LSU in Baton Rouge right out of high school, but marriage and fatherhood interrupted my education.
 In 1983 I finished my BA at the Shreveport campus. 
I also have a MBA from Amber University,  now Amberton University, in Garland Texas. 
Career:
 I started with Skyline Trailors off of Swan Lake Road. Then went to West and Co. (Gibson\'s), followed by Montgomery Wards, Western Electric, then Eckerd Drugs and finally AAFES (Army and Air Force Exchange). I retired in Dec 2012 from AAFES with 25 plus years of service. At the time of my retirement from AAFES  I was certified as an Equal Employment Opportunity (EEO) investigator and Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR) mediator. 

Health is very good now. I\'m using a Bipap machine that has improved my sleeping greatly. Without it I might not be here today. Then last year I had heart surgery which corrected several nerve bundles that where firing out of sync with the rest of my heart.
Memories:
 One memory that comes to mind in my early years is that all grades where in the red brick high school as we knew it. Playing throw back football at recess was a very rough game, many of us came home with clothes torn up.
 As I remember there were two baseball teams from Benton: Aces and Beavers. My Dad and Robert\'s were assistant coaches. Later years Robert A., Mike DeMoss, Hal and several others would get together for either a chess or a monopoly tournament, these where fun. 
A favorite memory I have from my  high school years is centered around my Dad. I would go with him out to a deer camp towards Bellevue to play poker with a bunch of older men. A dinner would be cooked, either BBQ , deep fried fish, or deer along with plenty of cold drinks. I would have a beer once in awhile. 
Two other memories that hold a special place with me are (1) playing a basketball games against the faculty and (2) playing a pickup volleyball match with Coach Newman. I remember one such match in I was paired opposite him across the net and I went up to block his return. I did, but the ball caught me right between the eyes and then landed inside his court and so I won the point, ouch...!
Do you remember the fad of yo-yo\'s, those were fun trying to do many of the tricks I could see being done on tv...Also, hola hoops even to this day I cannot keep them going...One of my fondest recollections was going to the soda shop in town, ordering a  Pepsi, dropping salted peanuts into it and then drinking this mixture, all while reading comic books.
 One year, not sure which, our class got together to help a charity drive by asking for donations from drivers going up and down Benton Road, do not remember how much we collected but I do remember it was more than what had ever been collected before from Benton.
Basketball was my go to sport in high school. I was okay and enjoyed playing even later in life. I had one AAFES assignment to the Azores for two years and during our stay I would go to the gym and get in a pickup game with some of military men station there. It was a challenge as I was in my early 40s and the guys may have been in their early 20s. I really enjoyed the competition. I learned that I could still keep up with the younger guys.  Once I got back into shape I realized I still had the skills. I could still flat foot jump and grab the rim.  There was one big difference though...after a game, I spent the next several hours (sometimes days) with my knees wrapped in ice. My team mates never knew this part of the story.
Pasttimes:
Over the years, I learned to play pool, golf, darts and bowling.  I currently bowl in a local league every Tuesday, except during hunting season.
Of course, board games have always been a favorite pasttime, especially, backgammon. 
Today I love playing board games like: Ticket to Ride, Stone Age, Power Grid and many other games that I cannot recall. My wife calls it obsessive. Kevin, my nephews and I go to a board game conventions here in Dallas and do nothing but play board games of various  types. These conventions last for four to five days and we play different types of games for 10 to 12 hours each day. While I love playing the games, the biggest joy I get is seeing and talking with people that come to the convention from all over the world. New Zealand and Israel being the fartherest. My current obsession with game playing is a computer based game, Civilization by Sid Meier, in which I play against AI.
My biggest passion right now is deer hunting, no surprise here as I have been hunting since I was about 8. I am a member of Sailes Hunting Club outside of Fryberg. Glen and I are the third generation of Hill\'s to hunt across these lands. 
 I also bought a piece of Oklahoma on which to hunt.  240 acres in the Buffalo mountains, with tall pines, a seasonal creek and rocky terrain. I\'ve built a 16x28 foot  off grid hunting cabin which has almost all the necessities needed to stay in the woods  for weeks at a time. If  I  need more then the town of McAlester is  just 30 minutes down the road. Tammy jokes that I didn\'t build the cabin until she became unable to camp. When she went with me, we sleep in tents and she cooked over a campfire. (Boy she could sure make a tasty campfire stew with biscuits). Now she says I\'m soft. I still go camping, but I sleep in a bed, with heat in the winter and a/c in the summer and cook on a propane stove.
My son in law Randy, hunts in the mountains outside of Denver. Every year I apply for a  Colorado deer tag. If I get lucky in the draw, I join Randy in the hunt. Unfortunately, I wasn\'t lucky this year.
My time with AAFES, allowed me to travel. Not only did we live in Arlington Texas for over 20 years, we lived in the panhandle of Florida (just north of Fort Walton Beach) for five years and at Lajes Field, Praia de Vittoria, Terceira Island, Azores, Portugal (now that\'s a mouthful) for 2 years while working for AAFES. If your not familiar with the Azores, they are an archipelago of seven islands in the Atlantic off of the coast of Portugal.  Additionally, I had temporary assignments in northern Italy and central England. Of course, I criss-crossed the United States during my career from Washington to Florida, from New York to California. Let\'s not forget Hawaii. I\'ll never forget the Arizona Memorial.
Tammy and I continue to enjoy travelling. Last year\'s trip to Peru to visit Machu Picchu and the Sacred Valley will always be the pinnacle of our travels.
 Most evenings find Tammy and I snuggled up in front of the television. Game shows like Jeopardy and Who Wants to be a Millionaire are favorites. We also enjoy reality shows on HGTY, the Food Network, and the History Channel. 
On the weekends, if we don\'t have plans at the lake or with the grandkids, Tammy and I enjoy visiting nearby flea markets and antique stores. Tammy collects depression glass and I am always on the look out for antique items from the milking industry amd other farm implements.","0","0","Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/69.0.3497.100 Safari/537.36","","0","0"),
