In 1983 I finished my BA at the Shreveport campus.
I also have a MBA from Amber University, now Amberton University, in Garland Texas.
Career:
I started with Skyline Trailors off of Swan Lake Road. Then went to West and Co. (Gibson\'s), followed by Montgomery Wards, Western Electric, then Eckerd Drugs and finally AAFES (Army and Air Force Exchange). I retired in Dec 2012 from AAFES with 25 plus years of service. At the time of my retirement from AAFES I was certified as an Equal Employment Opportunity (EEO) investigator and Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR) mediator.

Health is very good now. I\'m using a Bipap machine that has improved my sleeping greatly. Without it I might not be here today. Then last year I had heart surgery which corrected several nerve bundles that where firing out of sync with the rest of my heart.
Memories:
One memory that comes to mind in my early years is that all grades where in the red brick high school as we knew it. Playing throw back football at recess was a very rough game, many of us came home with clothes torn up.
As I remember there were two baseball teams from Benton: Aces and Beavers. My Dad and Robert\'s were assistant coaches. Later years Robert A., Mike DeMoss, Hal and several others would get together for either a chess or a monopoly tournament, these where fun.
A favorite memory I have from my high school years is centered around my Dad. I would go with him out to a deer camp towards Bellevue to play poker with a bunch of older men. A dinner would be cooked, either BBQ , deep fried fish, or deer along with plenty of cold drinks. I would have a beer once in awhile.
Two other memories that hold a special place with me are (1) playing a basketball games against the faculty and (2) playing a pickup volleyball match with Coach Newman. I remember one such match in I was paired opposite him across the net and I went up to block his return. I did, but the ball caught me right between the eyes and then landed inside his court and so I won the point, ouch...!
Do you remember the fad of yo-yo\'s, those were fun trying to do many of the tricks I could see being done on tv...Also, hola hoops even to this day I cannot keep them going...One of my fondest recollections was going to the soda shop in town, ordering a Pepsi, dropping salted peanuts into it and then drinking this mixture, all while reading comic books.
One year, not sure which, our class got together to help a charity drive by asking for donations from drivers going up and down Benton Road, do not remember how much we collected but I do remember it was more than what had ever been collected before from Benton.
Basketball was my go to sport in high school. I was okay and enjoyed playing even later in life. I had one AAFES assignment to the Azores for two years and during our stay I would go to the gym and get in a pickup game with some of military men station there. It was a challenge as I was in my early 40s and the guys may have been in their early 20s. I really enjoyed the competition. I learned that I could still keep up with the younger guys. Once I got back into shape I realized I still had the skills. I could still flat foot jump and grab the rim. There was one big difference though...after a game, I spent the next several hours (sometimes days) with my knees wrapped in ice. My team mates never knew this part of the story.
Pasttimes:
Over the years, I learned to play pool, golf, darts and bowling. I currently bowl in a local league every Tuesday, except during hunting season.
Of course, board games have always been a favorite pasttime, especially, backgammon.
Today I love playing board games like: Ticket to Ride, Stone Age, Power Grid and many other games that I cannot recall. My wife calls it obsessive. Kevin, my nephews and I go to a board game conventions here in Dallas and do nothing but play board games of various types. These conventions last for four to five days and we play different types of games for 10 to 12 hours each day. While I love playing the games, the biggest joy I get is seeing and talking with people that come to the convention from all over the world. New Zealand and Israel being the fartherest. My current obsession with game playing is a computer based game, Civilization by Sid Meier, in which I play against AI.
My biggest passion right now is deer hunting, no surprise here as I have been hunting since I was about 8. I am a member of Sailes Hunting Club outside of Fryberg. Glen and I are the third generation of Hill\'s to hunt across these lands.
I also bought a piece of Oklahoma on which to hunt. 240 acres in the Buffalo mountains, with tall pines, a seasonal creek and rocky terrain. I\'ve built a 16x28 foot off grid hunting cabin which has almost all the necessities needed to stay in the woods for weeks at a time. If I need more then the town of McAlester is just 30 minutes down the road. Tammy jokes that I didn\'t build the cabin until she became unable to camp. When she went with me, we sleep in tents and she cooked over a campfire. (Boy she could sure make a tasty campfire stew with biscuits). Now she says I\'m soft. I still go camping, but I sleep in a bed, with heat in the winter and a/c in the summer and cook on a propane stove.
My son in law Randy, hunts in the mountains outside of Denver. Every year I apply for a Colorado deer tag. If I get lucky in the draw, I join Randy in the hunt. Unfortunately, I wasn\'t lucky this year.
My time with AAFES, allowed me to travel. Not only did we live in Arlington Texas for over 20 years, we lived in the panhandle of Florida (just north of Fort Walton Beach) for five years and at Lajes Field, Praia de Vittoria, Terceira Island, Azores, Portugal (now that\'s a mouthful) for 2 years while working for AAFES. If your not familiar with the Azores, they are an archipelago of seven islands in the Atlantic off of the coast of Portugal. Additionally, I had temporary assignments in northern Italy and central England. Of course, I criss-crossed the United States during my career from Washington to Florida, from New York to California. Let\'s not forget Hawaii. I\'ll never forget the Arizona Memorial.
Tammy and I continue to enjoy traveling. Last year\'s trip to Peru to visit Machu Picchu and the Sacred Valley will always be the pinnacle of our travels.
Most evenings find Tammy and I snuggled up in front of the television. Game shows like Jeopardy and Who Wants to be a Millionaire are favorites. We also enjoy reality shows on HGTY, the Food Network, and the History Channel.
On the weekends, if we don\'t have plans at the lake or with the grandkids, Tammy and I enjoy visiting nearby flea markets and antique stores. Tammy collects depression glass and I am always on the look out for antique items from the milking industry and other farm implements.

