("4951","1","2018-07-14 13:05:40","2018-07-14 13:05:40","<em><strong><span style=\"font-size: small;\"> I came to Benton in the early summer of 1965 and started Benton Middle School as an eighth grader. Mrs. Stratton, Mrs. Nelson, Mr. Little were my teachers that I remember so well. All wonderful in their own right. We had just arrived back in the United States from spending almost 5 years in Bombay, India. I had just finished 4+ years in a British school where I learned British and World history before ever learning American history. I guess that fueled my love of history, genealogy and of travelling. Having been around the world by the age of 14 and experiencing many different cultures and religions during my working years has helped me to understand and respect people and their customs much deeper than the casual traveler. My high school years are a blur but Mr. Floyd was a guide post for me. Discipline.
We all remember our first love. My first love was from Benton and shall remain nameless, but she knows who she is. She was a sweet and beautiful young girl and grew into a sweet and lovely southern lady. There will always be a special place in my heart for her. I remember Friday night football games and the dances we had. I remember Mr. Penuell throwing myself and a few other kids out for doing the “Gator”. Such a lewd and suggestive dance back then but look at them now.
I grew up on 5th street just down a few houses from Roger Johnson and next door to Hubert Jones and then Debbie and Rhonda Hightower. Roger and I became friends and still are to this day as all my classmates are. Next door was Faye and Patti McDonald and they both are dear to me. Their parents were my second Mom and Dad and I miss them dearly. My Dad passed away just a few short months, in August of 1965, after we arrived in Benton. We had just started school and I remember a few of my friends coming to the house to be with me. Robert A. and Roger stand out. My Mom passed in 1985. I think about them every day and one day I will join them in God’s arms. Out of 13 in my family there are 6 of us left with my oldest living sibling being 86.
As I sit in a hotel room and write this I look back over the 48 years I have worked in the oil and natural gas industry. I am having fun and as long as I am having fun and have my health I will continue working. My job has sent me to some exotic places and some hell holes. The best place I have visited through my work is Italy. I loved it so much I have just returned with my daughter and granddaughter from my 10th trip to Italy. The worst place I have ever been was Uganda. I have really never feared for my life except there. Thankfully I befriended a Colonel in the Russian Army and he made sure I was safe. I repaid his kindness with 5 pairs of Wrangler blue jeans when I came home. They were the perfect size for his son and we were friends until his death in 2003.
As I mentioned earlier, my work has afforded me many adventures both here and overseas. I still travel almost weekly throughout the US and still enjoy the many different people I meet. I have been married and divorced twice. Debbie Corley McSpadden and I have two wonderful daughters who have made us both proud in many, many ways. Our eldest has three children with the oldest just having graduated high school and will enrolled at Texas A &amp; M Pharmacy School after completing her prerequisites at a local college (less expensive and just as good). The next oldest is a senior in High School and President of the Student Council and plays Volleyball and was just elected Homecoming Princess. Our oldest grandson is a sophomore and is destined for greatness on the baseball field. Our youngest daughter and her husband have two children. The oldest just celebrated his 7th birthday and steals my heart when he can name more dinosaurs than I can. I just gave him 4 dinosaur teeth that I found and he could name the dinosaur they came from. He is my paleontologist. My “little girl” just turned two and will steal your heart at a glance. She loves to dance.</span></strong></em>

I am always looking for the next adventure whether it be out looking for Native American artifacts of which I have close to 900 pieces or fossil hunting in West Texas. I have donated approximately 2000 fossils to several museums and probably have twice that amount stored in my garage. Our backyard is going to be a big puzzle to some paleontologist sometime in the distant future with all the fossils laying around.
I am now engaged (no date set yet) to a wonderful woman who has been by my side for 7 years now. I don’t deserve her but God knew what He was doing when He put her in my life. We love to travel and will do so until we can’t anymore. My health isn’t what it used to be and I suffer from RA and a few other skeletal diseases. I don’t move as fast as I used to and sometimes I fall but I get back up and tell God “thank you” for letting me back up. I have never smoked and never taken illegal drugs. I drink a little wine every now and then but never to the excess. I am at a point in my life where I enjoy the little things and wish that phase had come earlier in my life. I love to feed the birds and squirrels in my backyard and if you are a friend of mine on Facebook you know I love sunrises and sunsets.
I’ve made so many friends in my lifetime and I thank God for each and every one of them. I especially thank Him for my friends from Benton High School and the influence you have had on my life. Like it or not our lives are intertwined. I like it. Thank you each and all for you have influenced my life for the better. May God spread his Grace and Blessings over you for many more years.

Hal W. McSpadden

