("5080","1","2018-07-29 10:45:22","2018-07-29 10:45:22","When I think of my time in school, I was lucky.  I had all I needed.  My parents provided a loving home, with plenty of food and clothes to wear.  I had two younger brothers, David and Richard, a set of grandparents that lived 11 miles away and another that lived on the other side of the state--both of which it was a treat to visit.  If I went anywhere, it was mostly by bicycle--to school, other friend’s houses, or just to explore Benton.  I felt safe and was generally a happy young man.  School work came easy, partly because I listened and the young brain was able to reason out most stuff.  It helped with grades all through elementary, junior high, and high school.  Since studying was not one of my favorite past-times, I was lucky that I retained what the teachers presented in class.  It was harder in college--because I did not develop those good study habits.  It then became WORK!

Anyway, it all started in first grade in Bossier City at Plantation Park Elementary.  I became a young Benton tiger about halfway through the 1st grade when we moved to Benton--to a house on Larkin St.  I was a few houses down from Jone Huckabee, Butch Strange, Steve Rambo and around the corner toward school lived James Cox. One of my favorite pastimes was climbing the tall pine trees on the lot across from our house.   From their upper branches, on a clear day, I could see the buildings of downtown Shreveport.  That was the extent of my world.  We had three TV channels (well, 2 good ones and one fuzzy one) through which we sampled our news @ 6 and watched Marshall Dillon, I Dream of Jeannie and the first Hawaii 5-0.

I remember Paula Baker\'s first day, the sprinkly trough where we washed our hands in the cafeteria, all the teachers were nice--and they were IN control.  If you got in trouble at school, you were in trouble at home because you better respect your teacher!  My classmates were a neat bunch--the guys were just buddies and the girls were--well, girls!  Until the later years, when, I discovered, WOW, the best people EVER--girls!  Smarter, prettier and they held the biggest mystery of all--what made them tick.  One of my buddies (oh, maybe in the third grade and I don\'t remember who) taught me a valuable skill--fishing for \'chicken-chokers.\'<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-5074\" src=\"http://1969tigers.co.events/s/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/DSCN0138.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1200\" />  I was an older adult before I found out what larval state of some beetle the little beast was.  But it was one of those \'guy\' things that was cool at the time.  Of course sports were big--football, basketball, baseball(tried them all)--but, what I came to appreciate most--running!  I had a little speed and had the feeling of always wanting to be in front--the same feeling that gets me in trouble today (with a heavy foot) and not wanting to be behind anyone.

I worked during some summers in the hayfields, with Kenneth Hill, from \'could to can\'t\' work hours, and learned the value of hot, hard work which taught me that I did not want to do that for a living!  I don’t exactly remember when the conversation occurred(I think 4<sup>th</sup> grade) but Ronny Jimmerson and I decided we were going to be doctors—I don’t know why but it was something we discussed.  After Benton, I was fortunate enough to go to Louisiana College—and off I went with Gary Mayfield as a roommate.  I studied biology, chemistry and all of those classes to prepare to maybe study as a physician.  A classmate in physics class asked me to come to St. Francis Cabrini hospital where he worked as a respiratory therapist.  I didn’t know what kind of animal that was but visited and watched him go through the paces.  I was looking for some job to make extra spending cash and decided—hey, I could do that.  They were short-handed so I was interviewed and within a couple of days and some rudimentary inservicing, was working an evening or two delivering oxygen, giving breathing treatments, doing diagnostic electrocardiograms and I remember being scared out of my mind.  Every time I heard an ambulance siren, I would go pale and pray that they were not going to need me.  It was a lot to learn but I got to see what medicine was like on the emergency end of the spectrum.  We were used by some physicians to assist with putting in pacemakers, making changes on ventilators, and of course responding and assisting in the ‘Code Blue’ situations where everyone pitched in to save a life in trouble.  I saw death and suffering and every now and then—relief, because of something we gave.  So there was an element of accomplishment that made one feel—worth.

Well, as happens too often, the work and the income become worth more than the work toward the initial goal of a distant career.  I became a certified Respiratory Therapist and branched out to the other areas of the field.  Being credentialed of course gave you value, so other hospitals offered more benefits for the knowledge you attained.  I became a Registered Therapist and was able to go into management, taught in a therapist training program at Bossier General, was able to work with heart, lung and liver-transplant patients at Ochsner Medical Foundation, presented research studies at the national conventions—all being ‘close to’ that childhood prediction with Ronny.

It takes support, and I have a great support system—parents, a loving bride, an accomplished daughter, a son-in-law, and two of best-looking, genius grandsons—ever!  My parents have always been supportive of myself and two brothers.  My dad, now 90 years young worked for Texas Eastern as a ‘land’ man, surveying and managing land rights for natural gas being transported through our land.  His job took his ‘family’ all over this country, from Harrisburg, PA to Boise, IH to Houston, TX and to Shreveport, LA.  He and my Mom now live north of Houston where they are involved in their church and community—my Dad helped take care of those in the neighborhood needing those odd jobs than only a caring neighbor can.  When he cut down a tree, he dug up the stump also!  He does not believe in a job half done!  My Mom has a sweet heart and can grow anything!  You have an old rock—she can get it to root and grow into something beautiful.  Their yard is a garden just short of ‘Eden’.  She sings in the “Silver Belles”, a group of ladies that are most sought after for their beautiful sound.  My Mom and Dad raised me and my brothers in a loving, respectful manner and overlooked the occasional mess-ups that young men do.  Most importantly, they kept us in church, and attended with us—what I consider Job One for parents!  My brother David worked as a banking computer programmer and while at Benton was a star football running back.  He is enjoying retirement on a golf course just north of my parents.  His wife, Raquel, is a business owner from Lima, Peru.  Yes, they met while he was working at a bank there.  She is our newest family member who is now a naturalized US citizen!  They enjoy cruising around the course in their golf cart—when it is not so blazing hot.  My youngest brother Richard has been gone, now 6 years.  He worked for Continental Airlines and lived not too far from our parents.  He too played football at Benton and was a liked by all who knew him—I miss him.

My bride, Linda, is one of the smartest and talented women I know.  She is well-read and could inspire people to give of their talents that they did not know they had.  She helped recruit church members to participate in the Christmas and Easter pageants.  They would kick and moan during the process but she had a knack of getting them to agree to put themselves in front of the audience.  Successive years, they would come to her and ASK to be included.  She is a staunch follower of the tennis circuit and is knowledgeable about so many subjects.  Always a beauty, she has put up with me since 1973 after I saw her the year before across the auditorium at Louisiana College—and said, ‘Wow!’.  I have to give thanks for that chance meeting.  Out of our marriage came a daughter who inspires all who know her.  Grace from her mother, maybe a little respect for other people from me—the rest has got to be divinely given.  Ashley is the wife of Andrew, an Episcopal priest—a minister who is blessed with a wife who also ministers to those who know her.  She has a sweet heart, a sharp mind, like her mother and that something extra that just makes her likable.  She excelled in school, was a leader, was involved in the drama presentations in high school and college.  She was our county’s Junior Miss.  Just a very accomplished, genuine young lady.  A dad could not be any prouder of a daughter.  Andrew Cannan was smart enough to catch her.  He is a talented man, who loves gourmet coffee, cares for his family and his church and loves to fish!  He is from good stock and helps give a father peace of mind knowing his daughter is in good hands.  Our of their marriage has come the best part of getting older—the grands!  Harry is 8(coming up to 9), is good-looking, smart and involved in sports and all of the latest Marvel heroes.  He can read anything and right now Harry Potter is IN!  His younger brother, Myers has one of the sweetest hearts (when he is not trying to kill his older brother), loves Getter Robo and has a knack of being able to sing anything (even the Japanese praises to their hero robots).

Lucky man.  You betcha.  With that kind of support, you can accomplish anything!  And want to keep on looking for the good in this world.  In my later years, I am still working full-time.  Three 13 and a half-hour night shifts a week as a registered polysomnographic technologist (if you can say that, they give you the RPSGT title behind your name).  It is one of those rare professions where, in a single night, you can identify a problem—and fix it!—all in one night.  Talk about rewarding!  And frustrating.  People do not know what goes on in their sleep.  It can be frightening.  Trying to inspire people to accept and maintain their therapy options is a cross between the art of presenting to them what you observe and a crossing of your fingers that they believe you.  Those who are able to tolerate the therapy (of CPAP/BiPAP) long enough for it to become a habit—are much safer and get better sleep and have an overall better quality of life.  It is a good job for my older years.  Retire?  Yeah, maybe in a few years.  But as long as I can stay useful—why not?

For fun?  Linda and I are mostly homebodys.  We love good TV dramas (not much into the comedys since “Frasier”), Downton Abbey, Blue Bloods and the ‘Chicago’ shows.  Tennis (Linda’s favorite), My New Orleans ‘Saints’, (I even liked the Curling on the Winter Olympics!) are some of the sports we like.  I like (or try not to be frustrated) working on my computer.  I have just enough knowledge to mess things up royally, trying to tweak here and there for the best and effective-running machine.  Nothing is ever standard and there is always CHANGE.  It is becoming harder to keep up—but therein lies the Challenge!  And remember, I always like to be up front!

Well, I should probably stop here--that is enough about what has gone on in my life since my time as a Benton Tiger. But, overall while a classmate of young men and women whom I was fortunate enough to grow up with, it was a time that I remember as pleasant and memorable. I don\'t remeber but just a few instances of seeing fights or bullying or meaness. Our teachers all seemed helpful and fair. Those in my class, we just seemed to get along. Maybe I saw things through rose-colored glasses, but there did not seem to be inequality or class distinctions. We all in the end just want to be liked and included and not be \'different\'. I can only vaguely remember an incidence of name-calling but I don\'t even think it was at Benton. Even though it has been decades, I feel as though I could talk to anyone in the class with good memories. Now there are some of you I did not know well(and wish that I did). I did not consider myself a great talker--more a listener--so it was not in me to be brave enough to find out more of who you were. Some of you I only saw at school. Some I have been in your home or we attended church together with all its activities--so I know you better than others. Being a guy, I think I looked at friendships or relationships in a more simplistic manner. Things were just not complicated.

I do recall an incident that(now,when I think back)taught me a valuable lesson. I do not remember exactly when, but I am thinking it was about 5th grade. It was lunch time, I had gone through the line, picked up my meal and headed to an empty seat at a table that was mostly filled with the classmates I would normally eat. It was the table closest to the north entrance of the cafeteria. The only person I remember was James Cox. He had been there before I sat down. I don\'t remember any conversation or anything out of the ordinary. But suddenly, James took a salt shaker, unscrewed the top, poured it on my food, and left the table without a word. I did not have a clue as to why. Come to find out, evidently, a rumour(and who knows how they start)went around that, \'I did not like James\'! Now, there could never be a reason why anyone, especially me, would not like James. He was popular and likable because he was genuine and gentle and kind--and a valuable friend to have. I don\'t remember how we resolved to get to the truth, but it was one of those memories that taught me the value we place on our relationships and when threatened, how we might act to protect ourselves.  Compared to then, what do we see in the news today?  Usually more than salt is thrown.

I am blessed to have grown up with parents, classmates, friends, teachers, and adults in a community of small-town America. God smiled on the Alvarados when He inspired the Blue family(whose father worked with my Dad)to come and invite us to their church. In that church I came to make the most important decision of my life and sealed my future for eternity. If it were not for that decision, then the purpose of the life of \'Robert\' and all my trappings would have no value.

