("5112","1","2018-09-04 02:49:26","2018-09-04 02:49:26","The Past 50 Years

As we get ready to have a 50-year class reunion I want to start by asking for every class member to forgive me for not keeping in touch.  Since Paula started the face book page its easy to see many of you have kept in touch to some extent.  I wish I had.  I want to thank Hal McSpadden for being a much better friend to me than I have been to him.  He has kept in touch for many years.  I sent most of the following to Robert 20 years ago and he promised he would do the same.  However, he didn’t say when he would - but he has now and created us a wonderful site.  Thank you Robert!

___________________________________________________________________________


God has blessed me with a wonderful life.  It started by living in Benton from birth until my early 20’s.  I can’t imagine a better place to have been raised.  I am going to try to recount each year since I got out of Benton High School with the highlights of each year.  I am sure some of it will be correct and some of it close and some of it may just be the way I remember it.  I heard older gentleman say, “The older I get the faster I once was”.  I wish I had better recall of parts of it, but I don’t.

1969 – I was 17 when I graduated, and my parents made me go to college.  I wanted to work and continue to rope calves and try to improve where I could do it for a living.   But I was told I had to go to LSU Shreveport where I took the minimum of 12 hours, they made me, but they couldn’t make me try and I failed all 4 courses.  I guess I showed them, didn’t I?

1970 - 1973
The spring of 1970 I worked in the oil fields and practice roping calves at night.  The fall of 1970, after working in the oilfields in August and 100-degree days I thought college might not be so bad, so I was a late enrollee at Northwestern State University.  I got my first clock radio just before I went to college.  Because I was a late enrollee, I was given to the dorm called the barracks.  It was named that because that is what it originally was.  Back in the seventies integration was just being implemented and most black people were put in the barracks.  My first night there I got my new radio out and set it for 6:00 am.  I made two mistakes.  The first was not knowing how to shut it off, and the other was not thinking about what was played at 6:00 am on every southern radio station in the country in 1970 – “DIXIE”.   It was great to wake up to except I had it very loud because I didn’t want to be late for registration and I didn’t know how to turn it off.   I never did get it turned off, I had to unplug it.   When I got back to the dorm later that day I had a visit from the floor monitor and was asked why I was trying to start trouble.  No one believed that it was an accident.   When I got my first driver license I was 5’2” and didn’t start growing until I was 16.  By now I was 6’4” and 225 lbs. and I sure was glad because I got a lot of mean looks from some of my dorm mates whom were mostly black.  I think my size kept it to just looks.  I was moved in a couple of days.  I believe they thought I was a trouble maker.  I majored in agri-business and stayed at NSU for 5 semesters and then left and went to Northeast State University in Monroe, La.  They had offered me a rodeo scholarship if I won the most points on the rodeo team.  I came in second and only went one semester.   During these three years the war was going on and I drew a number of 225 in the draft lottery (my blessed life continued).  As terrible as the war was I was in my little world and never realized how horrible it was.  I never knew anyone that got killed or got hurt so it never really hit home.  I have had men who worked for me that struggle with mental and physical problems from that war and I have tried to help all I can.  I have a tremendous amount of admiration and appreciation for the veterans and what they did.

1974
I worked in a machine shop and learned how to weld.   I worked there for about 4 months.  I was roping a lot and I was getting better.  I also was introduced to a girl by the name of Linda Priest.  She was friends with a lady who worked with her and her husband roped steers and was a friend of mine.  When he introduced her to me I still lived at our house in Benton and he said this is a nice girl.  That was the last thing I was looking for was a girlfriend much less a “nice girl” which meant commitment and I didn’t want any commitment because that would interfere with my roping.  I offered her a coke and I remember that I thought she was pretty and seemed very quiet but nice and I never really thought about her much again.

1975
I had started to improve in my roping ability and was winning some money and being single it didn’t take much to live on, plus I was still living at home, so I quit working and decided to rope full time.   I had also started to rope steers in an event called team roping.  I won my first saddle in 1974 for runner – up in the all-around race (the all-around winner is the one who wins the most money).  Also, one of those terrible events happened in my life – my mother and father divorced.  I move to Shreveport with my Mother.   My brother Chip and sister Ann did also.  Scott was already living in Shreveport.

1976
I was rodeoing as much as I could.  I had started to travel out of state and was learning a lot about the world living in a camper on my truck.   I won my first state championship in calf roping and the all-around that year.  God was blessing me in so many ways, but I never acknowledged Him.

1977-1980
I traveled and roped a lot – I won 10 saddles, the use of a new truck for a year.   I made friends all over the country.  I wish I could tell you I was a good influence on the people who looked up to me, but I can’t.  I was drinking and carousing a lot.  To this day it’s my greatest regret that I never gave God the glory for how he was blessing me.  But He does have a way of getting your attention.

During these years my brother Chip traveled a lot with me.  He was the state high school champion calf roper and won a lot.  He was the best calf roper to come out of high school in Louisiana in a long time.  He went to McNeese University on a full rodeo scholarship.  He could, and still can, really rope good.  He has always been the best brother you could ask for.  We now work together each day and we have never had a crossword.   Back then the closeness we had was strained by our desire to win.  He wanted to beat me because I had taught him and was older and I wanted to beat everyone.  I was obsessed with roping and did a lot of things that I regret.  I had a bad temper and did some things I am not proud of and have asked God to forgive me many times just as I have as I write this.

1981 – The shooting
As I said earlier God has a way of getting your attention.  In 1981 he did mine.   I had tried for 3 years to win the all around in the Louisiana Rodeo Association and the East Texas Rodeo Association (ETRA) in the same year (no one had ever done it before and I don’t think since).  In 1980 I did it.  I will never forget waking up in a motel room on a Sunday morning after the finals thinking “is this what I have worked so hard for for 3 years?”  It was an empty and un-fulfilled feeling.  That was in December of 1980.

On February 21, 1981 at about 11:30 am I went by the apartment I lived in to check my answering machine and as I turned to enter a corrido leading to my apartment door I saw a burglar walking out.  He had a pistol and my deer-hunting rifle on his shoulder.  When he saw me, he started shooting.  I had a pistol in my coat pocket (as I said earlier, I wasn’t living a saintly life, so I always had a pistol) and shot twice but his bullet hit my trigger guard on my 25-cal. pistol as I was trying to put a round in the chamber and split his bullet.  Part of it went through my right thumb, right index finger and the tip of my next to little finger on my left hand, the rest of it went into my stomach, the very middle of my abdomen.  There was a wooden fence at my apartment where we stored firewood.  I thought I had run out of bullets and he was still shooting I jumped behind the wooden fence.  I was trying to get my knife out of my back pocket and I couldn’t, the end of my thumb was shattered and was bleeding a good bit, but I thought I had gotten it caught in the action of my automatic pistol.  He continued to shoot through the wooden fence.  So, I then decide that I would rush him and try to get my hands on him.  As I peeked around the corner getting ready to rush him I saw him running the other way, which was ok with me.  I didn’t know if there was someone else in my apartment, so I decided to go to the apartment office and call the police.  As I was headed in a fast walk to the office I noticed feathers flying out of my goose down jacket, the one I had just paid $100.00 for.  I stopped running to see how bad it was ripped.  I unzipped my coat and notice a hole in my flannel shirt (it was very cold and windy that day), I unsnapped my shirt and the cold air hit the blood running down my stomach and I got scared.  Only then did I realize I had been shot.

I got to the Apartment office and they called the police and the paramedics.  I was rushed to Schumpert Hospital and there must have been 15 people in there rushing around.  Back then there weren’t many people shot like there are today.  During all this a friend of my Mothers who was a Catholic Nun came in and said a Priest was waiting to come in and give me the last rites if I wanted.  Not being of the Catholic faith, I thought that meant that they were pretty sure you were going to die, now I know they do that if it’s serious.  I thought they thought I was going to die.  I said that I didn’t want him coming in.  I wasn’t going to give up.  I guess I sort of lost it then, but I will always remember the questions I asked myself: “If I die am I going to Heaven or hell”.  Even though I had been raised in and out of a Presbyterian Church, I wasn’t sure.  I know now that if you aren’t sure then you are probably going to hell.  I saw a girl just before I went into surgery that I knew from rodeos and told her not to let them cut my finger and thumb off.  You can rope without a thumb and you can rope without an index finger, but you can’t without both.
A couple of days later Dr. Eddie came in the room and said “I was a doctor in the war and saw a lot of gun shots and I have never seen anything like this.  He said we did exploratory surgery because we couldn’t believe the bullet just stopped – it stopped ½” from your aorta and just pushed your stomach lining – never hit anything.  The bullet came out on the emergency room table when they flipped you and that’s why we couldn’t find it.  He stood up and said, “God is trying to tell you something, you better listen”, and he walked out.  He was emotional about it and never talked about it again.

For many months after the shooting I was very careful.  Because I was shot in my right hand I learned to shoot as well with my left hand.



1982
During the latter part of 1981 I got married and had a child 6 months later.  During that time, we separated and when Robert was born I went back and tried again.   It was a terrible marriage.  All the horror stories from her pulling guns, knives, running her truck into mine were part of it.  Finally, I gave up.  I knew it was a matter of time until something bad happened to me or my son.  After the court battle (they thought I had some money left for me by my grandfather) I was broke.  All I had in the world of much value was the horse “Pudden” that had helped me win most all the championships.  It was either ask my mother for money to pay the attorney and CPA’s or sell him.  It was the 2nd biggest heartbreak of my life, the first was leaving Robert Alan my son.  I sold Pudden for $4,500.00 and watched him as he was hauled off and saw him look back at me.  It’s a look I will never forget.  Any desire to rodeo hard again was driving off.

1983
During the balance of 1982 I continued to do welding repair and named it North Shreve Welding.   I also continued to rope some.  I had a young horse that was ok but not nearly as good as Pudden.  I won enough to help pay the bills and I made some money on the welding work.   All during this time God was working on me and I never forgot that day in the hospital and my question of if I had died would I be in heaven or hell.  God sent me a job for a Godly man who had a future pastor living on his farm.  This future pastor was Dennis Aaron.  Dennis and I knew each other from high school rodeo days.  We talked a lot about Jesus and he answered many questions.  Looking back God had him in my life to help me understand what I needed to change and how I needed to live.  I will never be able to thank him enough for being patient and answering a lot of questions.   About 20 years later God allowed me to help build a Church for him know as Open Range Fellowship in Greenwood, La.

1984
In February I hadn’t had a paying job in 6 weeks.  The young horse was doing ok, but I just didn’t have the desire anymore.  I stilled loved to rope but I just wasn’t happy.

Then “the day” happened:
About 5:00am I woke up – made some coffee.  I just didn’t feel any joy or peace.  I know now you can think you are happy living in sin, but joy and peace only comes from God.  I walked out the back door of my mobile home that led into the shop at about 5:30 am and felt overwhelmed with a need to pray.  I had been in a Presbyterian Church as I said earlier but I don’t ever remember anyone other than the Pastor praying out loud.  It was a very quiet and private Church.  So, for me to pray out loud was very unusual and maybe a first.  But that is just what I did.  I ask God to forgive me for all the bad things I had done.  I told Him that I had done everything on my own and that I was through doing it my way.  I asked him to be the Lord of my Life.  I promised him that I would serve him for the rest of my life.  If that was overseas, in the getto, it didn’t matter to me, I just wanted to serve him.  I thanked Him for allowing me to live and if he wanted me to rope again I needed a horse and if he wanted me to be in the welding business I needed some work.   I had a tremendous relief come over me.  I went back in my trailer house and felt better than I had in many months.  I knew my life had changed but I didn’t why or realize how much it was about to.

During the next few hours I got 5 jobs and then later that afternoon Mr. Greg Lea called and asked my how much work I had going on.  I had done some work for Mr. and Mrs. Lea that he was pleased with.  He said he had just signed a contract to buy Prentis Clark’s farm in Elm Grove and he was going to need a horse barn with stalls, and a lot of fencing.  I worked all that year and part of the next for Mr. Lea, all by the hour.  I did a little over $100,000.00 worth of work for Mr. &amp; Mrs. Lea that year.

That day put me in business.  God had given me a direction.  Over the years I have worked many men who had gotten out of jail and couldn’t get a job anywhere else.  Sometimes it works out and sometimes it doesn’t.  I have an open-door policy that anyone that is having family problems, or any other problems can come into my office or stop me in the shop and talk about it.  I will pray with them and always try to pray for them afterwards.  I know God gave me this for a Ministry and as long as he keeps me in it that’s the way I will run it.   It’s His and I am the manager is the way I view my ownership.

1985
My Mother, whom I loved dearly died.  Mother had struggled with poor health for many years from emphysema and diabetes.  She moved to Florida and lived with her Mother and my brother Scott for a couple of years.  Mother stumped her toe in Florida while living there and it wouldn’t heal so she came back up here to be closer to her Doctor.
I was living in a double wide house trailer and she lived with me.  It never got better, and they had to cut her leg off below the knee, it still wouldn’t heal so they cut it off above the knee and it finally started healing.  Then the other leg got bad and they had to cut it off below the knee.  God was very merciful to my Mother and let her come home in October of that year.   Chip and I had made the top 15 Finals in the state of La. in Calf Roping.  Mother died that Wednesday and we buried her on Friday.  That was the first night of the rodeo.  Neither one of us roped that year and I’m sure mother will tell me about it when I get to heaven.  I know she would have wanted us to rope but I could hardly bear it, much less rope.   That was the last year that I tried to make the finals.  I went to a few rodeos but for all practical purposes I quit after Mother died.   She had been my biggest fan and I miss her dearly to this day.
Looking back, I quit while I was still competitive, but I knew to serve God I had to break free from a strong hold satan had on me, drinking and running around with my buddies.  I didn’t know it then but Proverbs chapter 1, verses 10 – 19 warn us about this very thing.  Verse 15 even says “don’t even set a foot on their paths”.   God’s fellowship more than filled the void.


1986 - 1999
During the early part of 1986 I felt it was time to find a girlfriend and hopefully one that was a Christian.  One of my buddies talked me into going to a bar that a friend from high school (Bim Wingert) mother owned.  We went 3 Saturday nights in a row.  The first one I almost saw a fight, the second I almost got into one, and the third weekend I tried to start one.  I woke up that Sunday morning and called my friend and told him that was the last bar I would ever go in.  I don’t think he thought I was serious, but I knew that was the last one for me.
During this time, I started reading my bible and read a scripture in Luke 11:9-10 that really touched my heart.  It says “And I say to you, ask and it will be given to you; seek, and you will find; knock, and it will be opened to you.  For everyone who asks receives, and he who seeks finds, and to him who knocks it will be opened”

I prayed and told God that I believed every word of the Bible and I believed that if I had the faith then he would send me a Christian girlfriend.  I promised myself that I was going to wait for God.  I figured God would send me a lady in a supermarket or a sales lady would come by the office but that’s not what God had in mind.

There was a cattle farm joining my property and they hired a new farm manager from Kansas that I knew.  His name was W R Duncan.  WR was a team roper and I had roped some with.   He came by one day and talked about a big hay barn they were talking about building and asked if I would like to bid on it.  Of course, I said yes and asked him to let me know as soon as the plans were ready.  He called in a few days and said he and his wife had a girl he wanted me to meet.  I never thought about God sending me someone on a blind date, so I told him I wasn’t interested in a blind date.  He asked if I wanted to bid on that hay barn and I said yes.  He said he was going to have the plans on the following Thursday and he would come by to pick me up and then we were going to pick up some girl by the name of Linda.

So, on Thursday I met Linda, for the second time.  This was the same “nice girl” that the same family had introduced me to in 1974.  I didn’t, and I don’t think WR remembered introducing us, but she did.  I had an uphill road to convince her that my horse wasn’t still the most important thing in my life.  I knew she was special the moment I saw her.  She was very attractive, but my spirit was attracted to the spiritual side of her most.  Linda had been living a Christian life for a long time.   We started talking and our relationship grew quickly and then we both knew we were falling in love.  Linda had married a man who had three sons and they had Stacey who was 6 when we started dating.  Linda’s first husband Fred had died from cancer at 40.  Stacey was just 2 years old when he died.  Stacey and I were close from the start, I guess she needed a daddy and I needed a daughter.   I adopted Stacey about a year later.  It is a privilege being her daddy.  What a great gift God gave me in her.  Joey our oldest stepson was a freshman at LSU, Freddy was graduating from High School that May, and Butch was in the 7th grade.  We married that September.  Now I had a ready-made family and on top of all that Linda got pregnant right off the bat.  What a blessing because Linda had been told she would have a very difficult time getting pregnant.  Nine months later we had Christine.  Then 2 years later we had Jenny.

Stacey has given us three grandchildren (Cade, Kyleigh &amp; Dres) and she and her husband (Neal Sauviac) are pharmacist and work for Wal Mart.
Christine has given us one grandchild (Ellie).  She was a manager for Anytime Fitness in Okla. and has moved back and is job hunting.
Jenny is our red head who has a gift of mercy and is such a gift, the icing on our cake.  She is single and has worked at Word of God ministries for several years and does a lot of photography (her degree from LaTech) on the side.   All three are very smart and beautiful girls, they get that from their mother.
The hardest job in the world is being a step parent but with Butch it was easy.
Butch lives in Leesburg, Va. and has given us two grandchildren.  He graduated from LSU with a degree in Physics.
Fred lives in Haughton and we have one granddaughter.  Fred works from home trouble shooting health insurance software.
Joey lives in Shreveport and we have one grandson.  Joey is a landman.

I am still amazed at what God did - He moved a man, the same man, back from Kansas, to give me another chance at that “nice girl”.   God gave me a great wife and marriage.  If I had to tell one person in this world something that I didn’t want repeated it would be her.  We have been married close to 32 years and never raised out voice to each other.  Certainly, we have had disagreements, but we work it out.

Also - Just before we married I asked God to give me the strength to stop dipping “skoal”.  I had dipped skoal for 18 years at the rate of almost a can a day.  That was just part of being a cowboy, but I couldn’t stand the thought of Stacey seeing me dipping.  Neither she nor Linda knew I dipped.  I got on my knees one morning and asked God based on the scripture to give me the strength to stop and I have never taken another dip, Praise God!  If anyone has ever dipped or smoked, you know how addicting a habit it is.  I thank God for helping me quit.

My Father passed away in 1998.  I got to visit a lot with him before he died.  The older I get the more I appreciate all he taught me and how he lived.  I had an interesting visit late one night at the hospital about his faith and I am sure I will see him again.


2000 – 2004
With kids in private school and cost of raising kids increasing I needed more income (looking back I probably needed to cut spending).  So, I decided in the latter part of 1999 that we need to grow North Shreve Welding &amp; Construction.  I bid on the largest job and the 3rd largest job we had ever bid on and we got them both.  Both were terrible jobs.  Overtime required by doing both jobs at the same time and Chip and I stretched too thin and not able to run the jobs ourselves led to a big loss.  In January of 2002 I had to make some cuts.  I let a very good secretary go and cut back on all spending.  I sold all excess equipment and some that I needed but could rent as needed.  I needed to raise all the capital I could to pay off debt.   I tried to lease out part of our shop and part or all our offices.  I was going to get a portable building for an office, just like I started with.   For the first time in a long time I was thankful to God for a job, a truck with gas and food for my family because I could see all that going away if it didn’t turn around.  There is a saying I have since heard “You will never know Jesus is all you need until Jesus is all you have”.  That was where I was.
I sold our house of 4500 sq. ft. and moved into a 1450 sq. ft. rent house and used the equity to pay the company debt.  I prayed to God and asked for his blessings again with the promise that I would never forget that he gave me this business as a ministry and I would run it as such if He allowed me to.

2005
In 2005 we were selected to furnish the steel for La. Boardwalk.  It was much larger than one welding shop could do so we built what we could, and sub contracted the rest out.  It was a very profitable job.  I used some of the profit and went into my first and last business partnership when I opened Gumbo Daddy’s restaurant at La Boardwalk and another one on Youree Dr.  I furnished the funds and my partner ran them.  Neither worked out, nor did two other locations I tried after buying him out.  I change the name to Food Shack and I tried one more - feeding the employees for Teleperformance Call center.  It has work out well and we just opened another one on Airline Dr.

I bought some land in 2005 just north of North Shreve on Hwy 71 and built a house where we live today.


2018
Our business, like most small businesses, struggles at times but knowing Jesus is in control and that he only wants the best for me allows me to keep the worry to a minimum.  I love what I do and don’t plan to retire or sell out as long as I have good health.  We do travel a lot more now and enjoy seeing all the country.  So far, our favorite is Jackson Hole, WY.

Now let’s see what I do: I get up at 5:30 AM, take a shower and do my Bible study (most days).  I struggled for years trying to get a good time to study my Bible till a friend shared in Sunday School class he had the same problem but one day realized that he always had time to read the paper in the mornings (like I did)  but couldn’t find time to read his Bible.  He asked himself which was more important, and I did the same.

I go to work at 6:45 am and leave no later than 6:00 pm.  I work most Saturdays from 10-2. Owning your own business means there is always work to be done.

I have lived a great life.   My health is good except for 25 lbs. of old muscle and chest that have dropped.  I still have light-red hair.  It’s not turning gray, but it is turning loose.

I don’t know what my future holds, but I know who holds my future.


