("5136","1","2018-09-27 20:11:32","2018-09-27 20:11:32","The Seniors of Benton High School 1968-1969

&nbsp;

In 1969, 36 students graduated from Benton High School.  Most had dreams of the future.  For a few, life changed hardly at all.

During my senior year, I made notes in a book given to me by Beth Mitchell, my mother’s best friend.

Here are a few excerpts from that book. Reading them now, the words are naïve. But inside, I’m still the girl who wrote those words.  The world has not erased the love for the people I shared life with so long ago, 50 years ago.  Even with all that has happened to me, I’m still hopeful about the world and still have a sense of expectation about the future.  So, on with it.  My 17-year-old girl thoughts in my last year of high school.

Our school was Benton High School, our colors purple and gold, our motto “Strength in Knowledge.”

“I believe I’m closer to my friends this year, my senior year.  We all realize we may never see each other again, after graduation, so we’re having a ball while we’re together.  We’ve had fusses, but now that things are evening off, our class is really what it’s always been, the greatest at BHS!”

“I consider a friendly friend, one who always speaks and always has a smile for you if you’re down.  I have several friends who are the ‘friendly friend’ type.

“A few of my favorite things are tacos, orange drink (Kokomo had an Orange Julius drink made with orange drink and orange sherbet and a parasol stuck in the top), sailor hats (what?), wide neckties, and Shelby cars (can’t believe I even knew what a Shelby Mustang was).

“Our favorite dances were the Funky? and the Four Corners.  (I think I remember the latter as an exaggerated knee lifting in rhythm to the music.)

“My favorite book is <u>Come My Beloved</u> by Pearl S. Buck.” (I also remember reading every book by Thomas Hardy I could find.) (I’m planning to reread the Buck book.)

“A favorite place to go is The Other Who.” (Help me.  I have no recollection.)

“I enjoy dancing and listening to records.”

“My favorite movies are BULLETT, ROMEO AND JULIET, GONE WITH THE WIND.” (Being from Benton, we didn’t go to movies much.)

“My favorite TV show is ‘Mod Squad.’” (So 60s!!)

“A few favorite things are the colors red, white, and blue; baby doll shoes; bangles; sandals; pant dresses; elephant-leg pants; shiny hose; and sideburns.”

“A few favorite celebrities are Tom Jones; John Fred and His Playboy Band; the Ventures; Booker T and the MGs; Aretha Franklin; Michael Cole; Steve McQueen; Natalie Wood; and Robert Kennedy.

“One nutty thing that happened to me was being felled by a single blow from a seventh grader in the gym.” (I remember a seventh-grade boy slid into my legs from behind, and I went down like a tree.  I remember Nan running up to me and telling me that I fell gracefully.  She was always trying to spare people’s feelings.)

“I dumped my plate on the cafeteria floor, forgot about it, and stepped in it.  Then I was rescued by a handsome gent.”  (I think I know who this was. 😊)

“We had a senior party at the Methodist Church.  About that party.  Whew!” (Y’all, we really never did much at our parties that was noteworthy.  And maybe that was a good thing.  It was a different time.)

“The senior class boycotted trig, went to the library, sat down at a table, and in walked Mr. White!”

“I visited NASA with my family in Houston.” (My cousin Hugh Jamison has worked at NASA for over 20 years.  He’s currently liaison for NASA and the private companies who build the SpaceX.)

“I was criticized for wearing a plunging neckline—with nothing to plunge.”

“Seniors in 5<sup>th</sup>-period P.E. managed to skip P.E. about three times a week.”

“We discovered Bill Bailey Carter had wrinkles behind his ears.”

Expressions used frequently—“Well, let it ride.”  “Boy, that was a cut—chop, chop.” “Well, he said he hated my guts.” “Groovy at the movie.” “I’ll just let it ease on by.” (Some of this remembering is pretty painful.  Gosh, we were so NOT worldly).

“Tom Merritt and Mike Morton were all state choices in football.”

“District 1-B All Stars in football were Tom Merritt, Kenny Thomas, Mike Morton, James Cox, Ronnie Horton, Danny Dunn, Gary Martin, and Robert Lawrence.”

“Great football TEAM!  Loved being a cheerleader!! The boys worked hard, our team took district, were quarter final champs.”

“Our basketball team was sub-district champ!  All-District players were James Cox, Robert Lawrence, and Kenneth Hill.”

In track, Tom Merritt ran the 100-yard dash.  Kenneth Hill ran the 880 relay.  Robert Alvarado ran the 100-yard dash, the 220-yard dash, and the 440 and 880 relays.  (Do you guys remember Kenneth and Robert Alvarado’s running skills?)

“The track team won 1<sup>st</sup> at Northwestern meet.”

“The track team won district.”

“The track team won regional.  Nan, Debbie Barclay, and I presented trophies.” (Y’all.  I LOVE track.  I still run some.)

“I was in the Beta Club, on the yearbook staff, senior class president, and co-head cheerleader.” (With Debbie Barclay!!! I remember we made that work just fine.)

“Our cheerleading team won second place at the Northwestern State Cheerleading School. We made badges.  Half the group were robbers; half cops.  I was a cop.  I think the robbers won.”

“The Miss Shere Khan Beauty Pageant was April 12, 1969.  Debbie Barclay did a Charleston dance.  Debbie Corley presented art.  Jone Huckabee performed a pantomime.  Janis Martin did a skit.  Joanne Sullivan twirled.”  (I remember helping Janis backstage.  All the girls had people helping them.  I think we were in Mrs. Stratton’s room and there was a ton of activity.)

The junior class was in charge of our senior prom.  The theme was Tropicana.  The music was by the Warlocks.  Prom was held Friday, May 16, 1969 at 7:30 pm. I still have the program, a napkin, my place card, even a tiny pencil we used for autographs.  My notes say that we went to the junior breakfast at 2:30 am and got home at 3:20 am.  It was a big deal to stay out that late.  I don’t remember the breakfast at all.

I still have the order form for my senior key.  I still have my senior key, my Betty Crocker Homemaker pin, my Beta Club pin, my class ring, and who knows what else.  😊

In my memory book, I wrote down some prices of the times.  Movies cost $1.50-2.00.  A basketball ticket was $.50-1.00.  Football ticket adult $1.75, student $1.25.  A shirt cost $6.00, a skirt $5 to $7.  Shoes cost $10-15.  A hamburger was $.35.  Gasoline was $.35 a gallon.

I still have my room assignment for the Northwestern Scholastic Achievement Rally for chemistry and trig.  That trig test was the hardest test I’ve ever taken except for the GRE.

“Lynn and I rode a tandem bike after school.” (This is why Lynn’s last name is Penuell now.) (We borrowed the bike from the Erhlinspiels.)

“Mrs. Partain—a good example of a person keeping her youth.  My French teacher.”

Our baccalaureate service was held at BHS stadium, Sunday, May 25, 1969, at 8 PM.  Mrs.  Nancy Mason played the processional “God of Our Father.”  Rev. Glenn Marr gave the invocation.  Rev. LeRoy Dickinson read scripture.  An ensemble sang “O Give Thanks.” Mr. David White read announcements.  The Reverend Leon C. Scott gave the sermon.  His message was that we owe something to our  fellowman, ourselves, and to God.  We owe our dedication and must use our abilities.  Rev. Marr prayed the benediction.  Mrs. Mason play the recessional.

From our graduation invitation: The Senior Class/ of Benton High School/ announces its /Commencement Exercises/ Wednesday evening, May twenty-eighth/ Nineteen hundred sixty-nine/ eight o’clock/ High School Stadium

The theme of our graduation was “Dover Beach” by Matthew Arnold.  I marched in with Debbie Barclay.  Speakers were Cindy Scott, Nan Inman, Robert Alvarado, and me.  From my family, my Aunt Nellie Batchelor, her daughter Pat and her husband E. Jack and their children Jack and Tonya, and my grandmother attended.  My parents and my brother were also there, of course.  After graduation, we went to Lynn Myers’ house for an ice cream party given by (who else) Mr. Charles Penuell!!!!!!

“Next for me means college.  Northwestern here I come.  I’m really a little frightened about the whole thing, but I suppose I’ll survive, everyone else does.  I’ve heard a lot lately about how wild everyone is there, but surely not everyone.  I’ll have to seek out some decent friends.  Hope my roommate’s groovy.  I’m taking potluck.”  (The second semester I roomed with girls from Bossier.  I’m still friends with them.)

I never got over my homesickness the year I was away at Northwestern.

After my kids were in high school, I finished college in education and went on to graduate school.

&nbsp;

There is no one way to live a life.  Whatever we’ve done, however we’ve lived it, we’ve carried each other with us all the way.  Even the ones no longer here—all those teachers and fellow students.  In no way are their memories diminished.

