("5141","1","2018-10-05 08:23:24","2018-10-05 08:23:24","I arrived in Benton during our 8<sup>th</sup> grade year, shortly after Hal.  The first classmates I remember meeting were Bill Bailey, Jone, and Mike Morton, probably because they attended the Methodist Church.

My dad was the Methodist minister.  Methodist ministers, in those days, moved in June every 3-4 years, unless you were the minister of a large church in a large city. (That trend / rule-of-thumb is no longer in place.) So when the bishop came to dad in the fall asking him to make this move, it was quite unusual.  <em>I believe a death within the conference had caused a need for many to move at this time</em>.  Dad &amp; Mom asked Carol and I about it and we said we would be happy to move.  I had not anticipated how hard it would be to change schools and friends during the middle of 8<sup>th</sup> grade. Hard. By the time we moved into high school, I asked Dad if it would be possible to stay until graduation.  I knew he would try if asked and I really wanted to stay with this awesome group of friends to the end.  I also knew that meant Carol would probably not graduate with her Benton class. My wish was granted and I was and have been forever grateful.

I graduated from Centenary College with an education degree and then got my MEd from LSU Shreveport, attending nights and summers.  It was in the earliest days for LSUS and they were flying in the professors from Baton Rouge.

My first teaching job was at West Shreveport Elementary School in 1973.  We had over 700 students and not one bus.  They all lived within walking distance, a matter of a few blocks.  In those days it was 100% AA with a mixture of black and white teachers.  The little cheering squad that I managed called us the Oreos, which is how I learned to laugh and make light of our differences and speak openly about color. I had a lot to learn.  I considered myself open minded, liberal, and caring. But until one has been there…  One morning Laura knocked on the classroom door, earlier than doors were to be opened.  I asked what she needed and she told me Joseph was crying. Joseph was her cousin, also in my 6<sup>th</sup> grade classroom.  I asked if she knew why.  She said he’d found his mom that morning, in her bed, dead.  I got Joseph and Laura and brought them into the room and asked about it.  He did not know anything else to do but to come to school, to follow his normal routine. I took him to the principal who was able to get in touch with a grown brother who then stepped in. I cry today thinking about it and wondering how Joseph is doing.  I can’t imagine making that discovery as a child.  In that same school, not in my classroom, a second grader showed up one morning, dressed as he had been the day before but with grass and debris in his hair and quite disheveled.  When asked, he said through tears that his mama didn’t love him.  He had proven that by sleeping in the park that night and no one coming for him.  The principal was all over that and we were all so grateful.  Much was troubling about that whole setting, but in that 2<sup>nd</sup> grade mind there was no gray area.  I had twin 6<sup>th</sup> grade boys who sucked their thumbs and no one said anything; a very skinny little guy named Thomas with the worse speech impediment I’d ever encountered, but no known teasing; a girl 240# and I never heard them ridicule her. They were precious children. I learned so much, loved so many, and had to open my mind and heart more that year than I ever dreamed possible; I was totally wiped out by the end of May.

My dad, a big Boy Scout Leader, had met with a leader from Wyoming who lived and helped at a Youth-For-Christ camp just outside Jackson Hole.  This was a brand new camp and I could apply to be a worker-bee at the camp, pay to live there and work and get no payment.  Who would do that?  Me.  Daddy was convinced that I could let Carol sub-lease my apartment for the summer and head up there to help my heart and mind heal a bit.  He was so right, of course.  I got in my little Chevy Vega and took off, my mom a nervous wreck.  It was a great summer.  While there I applied for a job, had a phone interview, and got a teaching job at Benton Elementary.  I was beyond excited.  Ms. Carrington was teaching there, Jodi Newman (last name???)  was a secretary there, I taught Coach &amp; Mrs. Mason’s precious daughter, Angela, and taught alongside Ann Whittington and Cindy Stinson (Ford’s first wife), among many other fine people.  (Those are names I know most of you would recognize.) Sometimes I’d stop by to visit with Nan on my way home, either in her cute dress shop or at home.  In those years I got to see Ginger and Glen several times; I think I was already in Dallas/Garland when Natalie came along.  Valcar was always at work when I stopped by so I don’t remember ever seeing him in those days.

In 1976 I married Sid Davis, also at Centenary. He was a music major and through the recommendation of my college choir director he auditioned for Fred Waring and the Pennsylvanians, a traveling music show.  That meant he would live in PA most of the year where they lived and rehearsed in an old hotel and music hall in Delaware Water Gap and then went on the road with their show, coast to coast and border to border.  I’d fly to Ames, Iowa, and be with Sid and the show for Thanksgiving, he’d come home for an extended time at Christmas, and then I’d fly to wherever he was over the Easter holiday, L.A. one year and Chicago the next. Summers were spent at East Stroudsburg State College (living in the dorm) where the Pennsylvanians hosted music workshops, rehearsed, and had concerts throughout the summers. It was an unusual beginning, but we made it, celebrating our first two anniversaries with those amazing friends.

While Sid was with the Pennsylvanians I lost my dad.  He was my heart and I thought I would never recover.  He remains 55 years old in my eyes.  Time truly does help, but I continue to think of him daily and still miss him.  He and my mom created a very loving home. It was full of freedom, trust, open minds, love, support, and a strong faith. His words were kind and true, his heart big and inclusive, and we always felt loved.  We laughed a lot. The words “I love you” were rarely said, but always known. It was a very happy home.  He called many of the football games and I still have the cowbell he’d ring when there was a touchdown. He was the finest of men.

We moved to Dallas/Garland, where I taught the homebound for Richardson ISD and then taught in Garland ISD.  Child 1, Taylor, and child 2, Meredith, were born in Dallas.  In 1986 we moved to our permanent home of Houston, TX, and child 3 (Peyton) was born here.  Taylor and his wife and 2 step-daughters live in Ft. Worth, Meredith lives in Houston and I try hard not to call on her too much, and Peyton and her husband (from Nepal: a nice, peace-loving, husband and father) and their twin boys (my GRANDS!) live in Ft. Worth. All children and GRANDS are Texans.  Sid was director of music ministries and fine arts at FUMC in Garland, then Chapelwood UMC in Houston, and now St. Luke’s UMC in Houston.

Just as we started at St. Luke’s in 1996 Sid was diagnosed with Multiple Sclerosis.  We had much to learn.  Nothing remained the same; everything changed. My first 20 years of marriage had one look and feel; my last 22 years of marriage another.  We all had to work hard.  We had to file some rough edges, jump some rivers, build some bridges, change some expectations, hold hands, forgive, and continue to love one another when it was not easy to do.  (Some of you know exactly what I mean.) Sid is in a wheelchair, still working non-stop (blessing), but independence is a thing of the past. A number of years after the diagnosis my children and I had a great cleansing conversation.  We all said things we wish we’d been able to share earlier, but the timing was just not right.  Boy was that nice! I do have great children! We had to learn how to follow Will Rogers’ wisdom: “Don’t let yesterday use up too much of today.”

I know I am not alone in experiencing all these life/health changes. Some of you are care givers or possibly receivers.  It was not a journey either of us expected to take.  After all, we were young (relatively), healthy, strong, faithful, and kind people.  I don’t believe this was God’s will, it just was.  We have been able to weather this new life setting through strong family support, love for one another, therapy, and a strong faith.

I lost Mom in 2009.  She was my rock with Sid and MS, and with my children throughout everything.  Everything. She was the best! I miss her every day!

I retired from teaching in 2010, having taught +30 years, and I have been working for the Society of Petroleum Engineers ever since.  For 5 years I worked in the training department.  I did no training; I knew absolutely nothing about engineering, oil and gas, NOTHING.  I managed the logistics and learned a whole lot about a world that was completely foreign to me.  I managed classes in Bakersfield, Farmington, Denver, Tulsa, and then got to travel to Amsterdam and Dubai.  Amazing for this Mississippi/Louisiana girl. I have loved it all. When oil and gas took a dive our training department staff went from 6 to 1 and I was fortunate to move within the office to the OTC group.  For the past 3 years I have been the administrator for the Offshore Technology Conference.  Another world of learning.  The logistics for this huge event of 65,000 – 100,000 attendees representing &gt;100 countries, +2000 exhibiting companies from 40 countries, presenting +350 technical papers <em>(I had never even heard of a technical paper) </em>was completely different from the training scene. My learning continued as I took charge of the signage for the show (OMG), the staging guide for all the rooms used throughout the show, the catering for +20 breakfasts and luncheons and feeding the staff and contractors, and for the housing of staff and contractors.  This is a crazy world.  I had no idea that when you attended an event, if there was a trash can in that room, someone had written that down and ordered it.  If you forget to ask for a trashcan, there is not one in the room!  If you order a marker board, do not assume there will be markers or erasers, unless you write that down and order it.  And learning about the $$$$$ … again, OMG.  But it has been quite a ride and I feel so blessed.  So. Blessed.

In 2012 came colon cancer and surgery.  It was caught very early, stage 1, no chemo, fabulous doctors, and now I’m in the survivor’s camp, which is 5 clean years.  Oh my goodness!  Between MS and cancer we remain indebted (on many levels) to the medical center here, Baylor, Methodist &amp; MD Anderson.  That is a fine reason to keep working; the bills and medicines and treatments never stop!  Several of you have experienced cancer or have a loved one with it.  It is mean, but the research community is making huge strides in the field; MS is much the same, but it never goes into remission, there is no surgery to help, and there is much to learn about it.

But I must say, with those grandbabies in Ft. Worth, I’m giving serious thought to permanent retirement.  They fill my heart with joy and delight!  I need to travel!

Thank you, dear friends, for being who you were/are and accepting a preacher’s kid at a very awkward time in her life!  BHS holds very, very, very fond memories for me.

MS can turn on a dime, but at this day and time I plan to be there. I am so looking forward to seeing everyone who is able to get there.

This was too long, but 50 years! (49) Y’all!  That’s a long time!  Ok, I know you know that, I just needed to say it.  Just a few class memories below:

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<strong>SOME CLASS/BENTON MEMORIES            </strong>

In the 8<sup>th</sup> grade Gary Martin was sent to the cloak room by Mrs. Nelson.  At some point he went out the second floor window and came back to class through the door, pretending to be tardy and arriving for the first time.  I seem to remember the whole class trying to stifle the laughter.  I’d love to know if this is an accurate memory.  It still makes me smile!

Massive notes had to be taken in Mrs. Spencer’s science class. We copied pages and pages of questions or fill-in-blank assignments.

In Mr. Little’s social studies class memorizing all those parishes and the seats; staying in from recess to retake the exam until you could pass. Outlining every chapter of that textbook.

I was caught cheating (I called it helping a friend) by Mrs. Stratton.  She was so beautiful and so kind and I was so embarrassed.  I had let Jone copy a homework problem.  I had made a stupid mistake, which was, of course, also on Jone’s paper.  Totally undeniable.  We were both horrified.  Then I had to go home and tell my mom.  UGH.  Humiliating all the way around.  Big lesson learned.

The first girls to offer friendship were Kay Russell and Aileen Strickland.

Judy &amp; Karen were Beatles fanatics like I’d never seen before.  I was fascinated.

I had never known twins that weren’t identical. (My grand babies are fraternal.)

The school was so much bigger than any I’d ever attended, but Bill Bailey assured me that it would make sense soon and I’d be able to make my way to the office area independently.

Attending the murder trial at the courthouse with Coach Newman and the civics class.  Fascinating.

Studying for those tests at the Academic Rally each year at Northwestern is another memory. One test required that we ask Coach Newman to excuse us from PE so we could study. One day I asked him to please say no; I did not want to go study, I wanted PE. He smiled and made it so. Mom made me a “rally dress” each year for that trip.  I don’t remember being too perplexed by algebra, home economics was a bit strange, chemistry was difficult but we did ok, and shorthand was…I remember taking the dictation for the shorthand test, knowing full-well I’d gotten it.  Then I saw we had to transcribe that on an electric typewriter.  We did not know how to turn them on nor how to get the paper into the carriage! It took a few tries to realize the gentle touch needed, but once we got that under our belts, all was well.  We nailed it!

Putting together pictures and captions and pages for the yearbook.

Gary Mayfield came to our group and brought jazz – fun to watch him at the piano.  He always seemed happy and was very kind.  Years later I would attend his wedding.

I loved singing with Mike DeMoss; he had a beautiful voice.

Beta Club – membership controversies, a trip or two and Mrs. Vallery.  I loved Mrs. Vallery.

Studying algebra with James Earl and Chemistry with Bill Bailey and Tom.  Fun!

Band.  Oh my gosh, this might require a book. Between Mr. Hardin (who was great) and Mr. Griffen (great) was a band director whose name I thought I would never forget.  I have forgotten.  It was a very rough year.  Therefore, Mr. Griffen had a lot of repair work to do.  Our first show, I believe in Sarepta, was a disaster. Total. Disaster.  On the bus to the game I remember marking the turns in the music for some of the newbies. That was a pretty clear sign.  But we had to move forward. I can still hear my mother’s laughter from the stands; she could not stop. She had volume and an undeniable sound.  Mr. Griffen was standing at the steps to the stands, shaking his head, and with one hand on his head and the other holding on to the railing. We were a mess on that field, running into one another, very few people playing (Bill Bailey had shouldered his saxophone and was hollering out turns), Robert McKenzie nailing a few people with his trombone when either he or they would miss a turn, then the cursing in the midst of that block formation that was no longer a block.  And yet, somehow we made to the sidelines to play for the majorettes to do their routine.  They were probably great; I just have no memory beyond our fiasco.  Half-time shows got much better after that. Under Mr. Griffen we played at the opening of the Hemis-Fair in San Antonio. His son, who played French Horn with the San Antonio Symphony, joined us.  We were good!  Natchitoches Christmas Festivals. Concert season and competitions. One year we had a very difficult piece for sight-reading competition and we did not feel our score would be good; we did not sound good.  In the end we were the only school to receive a 1.  The score sheet indicated that we received that score, not because we sounded great, but because we were the only school in the competition to get all the way to the end together!  Mr. Griffen had given us very good guidance to make that happen.

Aside: The Griffen came to Benton from Ferriday where Mrs. Griffen had taught Jerry Lee Lewis the 3-4 chords that he knew and used to become famous.

I loved playing in the Ponytail League, girls softball, during the summers.  Such fun!

Jone and I often walked to school.  Many of those walks were used to study for the test of the day. I loved walking to school with her. Jone taught me the importance of keeping a promise.  If she promised you she wouldn’t tell, she wouldn’t tell.  She was the first person that I knew who would actually keep her promises no matter what.  I also remember helping her during the Miss Shere Khan pageant.  Thanks, Paula, for the reminder of all that camaraderie.  What fun!

I remember, I think correctly and unbiasedly (is that a word?), that we had the absolute best Jr/Sr Prom.  Bill Bailey knew the people who handled the decorations for the Plantation Ball, which had just happened at the Palmetto Country Club. Our décor was the best ever.  Then we made all those ceramic favors.  Mike Morton’s mom had the ceramic shop and I think it was Janice Ennis who led a big team of people to get that done.  I can’t remember who made the huge backdrop for the photos (Janice, was that you as well?), the moon with the roses.  Beautiful. Paula’s dad made large columns for us to use in decorating. I remember that our class rings arrived while we were out there decorating.  Coach Newman had just commented on how he was always taught that red and pink DID NOT go together and the whole room was red and pink.  If memory serves me well, he used the breaking of the red/pink rule to allow him to break the ladies-first rule and the boys got to go into town and get their rings first. Is that an accurate memory?

Football – oh my.  What a ride!  The whole town lined up behind the buses, band and cheerleaders and pep squad and teams, as we went to games.  Mom always had a thermos of coffee for her and dad and one of hot chocolate for Carol and me. Dances after the home games were so much fun.  My parents chaperoned many of those.  We had the longest regular season winning streak of any high school at any level in the state.  I wonder if that record still holds. We couldn’t quite get those final state play-off games, but we were so good.  The excitement was amazing and we all benefitted from it, town and students and school and families.  I remember the minister praying before a play-off game in Ville Platte and he talked about fish swimming in our stomachs – he lost me after that.  I couldn’t keep my eyes closed and couldn’t continue to listen. That’s a weird memory.  Many of our football heroes were also stars on the basketball court and in track.  I remember watching David &amp; Danny Dunn run the hurdles during track season.  They made it look so easy; I still don’t understand how people do that.

I remember Roger invited Bill Bailey, Nan, and me to take a senior-year deep-water fishing trip. Bill and I had gotten permission, we were excited. Nan got engaged. That ended that.  Thank you Roger for trying!  It was a blip in time, but I remember.

I loved Mr. Floyd.  But when he took that paddle to James, I was pleased that he busted his thumb during one of the hits of that tirade.  To me, his actions were so troubling.  It was hard to make that fit with the teacher that I loved.  It is still difficult.  I did not hear or see what Charles heard and saw.  I’m sorry that was going on. I loved Mr. Floyd.

I received a $1 a week allowance.  $.10 went to church and the rest was mine. I would often use $ .50 to put 2 gallons of gasoline in our VW. Daddy said that would allow me to travel 40 miles.  Bill Bailey and Paula would often travel with me as we simply rode the roads of Benton. I was very careful to stay within my 40 miles so I could keep doing that. Such freedom.

The church choirs would sometimes combine for Christmas or Easter cantatas. I remember that when singing in the Baptist Church, Robert’s mom would have the soprano solos; when singing in the Methodist Church, my mom would sing the soprano solos.  Both pillars of their choirs.

Loved the soda fountain at Parker’s.

Riding bicycles everywhere; being home by dark.

Meals around the table. Washing and drying dishes.

One summer Paula and I both had swimming memberships (or whatever) at Palmetto. It was a great summer.

I remember when Frank and Nan came to town and captured hearts. They were cute/handsome, smart, and kind.  And then there was Nan’s Georgia accent coupled with those dimples. And, she made her own clothes. Oh my goodness! She was a wonderful person, through and through.

I remember Charles getting a pay-check once and it was his first with a recent raise.  He went to the bannister on the second floor, leaned over and hollered down the stairwell, “I don’t want this raise; take it back.” I asked why he was upset and he explained that the raise had put him into another tax bracket and his take-home pay was less than before the raise. I did not completely understand that, but I believed him.

I remember James’ home was a happy one – all those children.  His mom was great! They had a jukebox that made parties such a happy time. James and I had a birthday party together at least once.  Our birthdays are 4 days apart.

I remember Annie being in a horrible wreck, I believe our junior year.

I remember Brenda Nickelson doing her hand jive.  She was funny!

Sorry, but one memory triggers another!

I’m going to stop with this last one, which was a big one for me.

When we were juniors, preparing for the prom, Mr. White called the officers to the office.  I think it was the class officers: Debbie Corley, Hal, Robert, and myself.  It seems Bill Bailey was there but I’m just not sure. The issue to be addressed had to do with inviting the librarian, Ola Mae Flucas, to the prom.  All teachers received an invitation and were allowed to bring a spouse or date.  At the time she was Ola Mae McClendon and not married.
<ol>
 	<li>Would she receive an invitation?</li>
 	<li>Would she be allowed a date?</li>
 	<li>Who would sit with her and her date?</li>
 	<li>How could we set up the banquet tables to offend the least number of people?</li>
</ol>
I don’t remember any of us considering this a problem until it was presented as a problem.  We really liked the librarian.  I may have been quite naïve and have a skewed memory; I’d love to know how others felt about this meeting.

My memory is that we said of course she would receive an invitation and why wouldn’t she be allowed to bring a date (I think she was engaged at the time).  #1 meant that a black person would sitting among us at the banquet. #2 meant there would be 2 black people sitting among us at the banquet. One of us suggested that we have round tables rather than the long banquet tables.  I volunteered for me and my date to sit at her table; I believe Hal or Bill Bailey volunteered, as well.  Perhaps we all did, I just don’t recall. We were told we (the officers) could not do that because we needed to be at the head table. Roadblocks.  And it was serious business in that office. We left, as I recall, with #3 &amp; #4 on hold.  She would be issued an invitation and allowed a date. I left that meeting feeling that our class was full of the finest guys and girls in the school and this would not be a problem.  The problem for this one was the adult in the room; I know he may have speaking for many.

I went straight to Charles, completely undone and worried.  Charles said not to worry. The librarian’s office has a pipe that runs through the floor into the office area.  He said she probably heard everything and would probably decline the invitation.  That, too, made me sad. I went to the library, handed her the invitation, told her we really wanted her to be there, she declined, and I asked her to think about it. The next day I went back to her and she assured me that she greatly appreciated receiving the invitation and wished she could attend, but she would need to decline. I left, and I believe I went back to Charles. He was right and I was sad. I don’t remember any of us talking about that meeting in the office that day, but I was proud that none of us had spoken offensively but one.  It was a new time and the implementation of equal rights (already &gt;10 years old by law) would get much harder once we left those halls.  But it was a meeting that began change in my heart and mind.

My dad was a huge sounding board for me in those days and gave great leadership by example; Charles was my go-to person at school. Thank you, Charles. You are such a good man. And you were smart enough to look for your soul-mate among our fine group! So glad, Lynn, that you slowed down just enough for him to catch you and become part of us.

This was a hard assignment.  Thank you, Robert, for making it happen! I’m so glad there are no grades. NO, Charles, NO GRADES!

