("5142","1","2018-10-05 08:23:59","2018-10-05 08:23:59","I arrived in Benton during our 8<sup>th</sup> grade year, shortly after Hal.  The first classmates I remember meeting were Bill Bailey, Jone, and Mike Morton, probably because they attended the Methodist Church.

My dad was the Methodist minister.  Methodist ministers, in those days, moved in June every 3-4 years, unless you were the minister of a large church in a large city. (That trend / rule-of-thumb is no longer in place.) So when the bishop came to dad in the fall asking him to make this move, it was quite unusual.  <em>I believe a death within the conference had caused a need for many to move at this time</em>.  Dad &amp; Mom asked Carol and I about it and we said we would be happy to move.  I had not anticipated how hard it would be to change schools and friends during the middle of 8<sup>th</sup> grade. Hard. By the time we moved into high school, I asked Dad if it would be possible to stay until graduation.  I knew he would try if asked and I really wanted to stay with this awesome group of friends to the end.  I also knew that meant Carol would probably not graduate with her Benton class. My wish was granted and I was and have been forever grateful.

I graduated from Centenary College with an education degree and then got my MEd from LSU Shreveport, attending nights and summers.  It was in the earliest days for LSUS and they were flying in the professors from Baton Rouge.

My first teaching job was at West Shreveport Elementary School in 1973.  We had over 700 students and not one bus.  They all lived within walking distance, a matter of a few blocks.  In those days it was 100% AA with a mixture of black and white teachers.  The little cheering squad that I managed called us the Oreos, which is how I learned to laugh and make light of our differences and speak openly about color. I had a lot to learn.  I considered myself open minded, liberal, and caring. But until one has been there…  One morning Laura knocked on the classroom door, earlier than doors were to be opened.  I asked what she needed and she told me Joseph was crying. Joseph was her cousin, also in my 6<sup>th</sup> grade classroom.  I asked if she knew why.  She said he’d found his mom that morning, in her bed, dead.  I got Joseph and Laura and brought them into the room and asked about it.  He did not know anything else to do but to come to school, to follow his normal routine. I took him to the principal who was able to get in touch with a grown brother who then stepped in. I cry today thinking about it and wondering how Joseph is doing.  I can’t imagine making that discovery as a child.  In that same school, not in my classroom, a second grader showed up one morning, dressed as he had been the day before but with grass and debris in his hair and quite disheveled.  When asked, he said through tears that his mama didn’t love him.  He had proven that by sleeping in the park that night and no one coming for him.  The principal was all over that and we were all so grateful.  Much was troubling about that whole setting, but in that 2<sup>nd</sup> grade mind there was no gray area.  I had twin 6<sup>th</sup> grade boys who sucked their thumbs and no one said anything; a very skinny little guy named Thomas with the worse speech impediment I’d ever encountered, but no known teasing; a girl 240# and I never heard them ridicule her. They were precious children. I learned so much, loved so many, and had to open my mind and heart more that year than I ever dreamed possible; I was totally wiped out by the end of May.

My dad, a big Boy Scout Leader, had met with a leader from Wyoming who lived and helped at a Youth-For-Christ camp just outside Jackson Hole.  This was a brand new camp and I could apply to be a worker-bee at the camp, pay to live there and work and get no payment.  Who would do that?  Me.  Daddy was convinced that I could let Carol sub-lease my apartment for the summer and head up there to help my heart and mind heal a bit.  He was so right, of course.  I got in my little Chevy Vega and took off, my mom a nervous wreck.  It was a great summer.  While there I applied for a job, had a phone interview, and got a teaching job at Benton Elementary.  I was beyond excited.  Ms. Carrington was teaching there, Jodi Newman (last name???)  was a secretary there, I taught Coach &amp; Mrs. Mason’s precious daughter, Angela, and taught alongside Ann Whittington and Cindy Stinson (Ford’s first wife), among many other fine people.  (Those are names I know most of you would recognize.) Sometimes I’d stop by to visit with Nan on my way home, either in her cute dress shop or at home.  In those years I got to see Ginger and Glen several times; I think I was already in Dallas/Garland when Natalie came along.  Valcar was always at work when I stopped by so I don’t remember ever seeing him in those days.

In 1976 I married Sid Davis, also at Centenary. He was a music major and through the recommendation of my college choir director he auditioned for Fred Waring and the Pennsylvanians, a traveling music show.  That meant he would live in PA most of the year where they lived and rehearsed in an old hotel and music hall in Delaware Water Gap and then went on the road with their show, coast to coast and border to border.  I’d fly to Ames, Iowa, and be with Sid and the show for Thanksgiving, he’d come home for an extended time at Christmas, and then I’d fly to wherever he was over the Easter holiday, L.A. one year and Chicago the next. Summers were spent at East Stroudsburg State College (living in the dorm) where the Pennsylvanians hosted music workshops, rehearsed, and had concerts throughout the summers. It was an unusual beginning, but we made it, celebrating our first two anniversaries with those amazing friends.

While Sid was with the Pennsylvanians I lost my dad.  He was my heart and I thought I would never recover.  He remains 55 years old in my eyes.  Time truly does help, but I continue to think of him daily and still miss him.  He and my mom created a very loving home. It was full of freedom, trust, open minds, love, support, and a strong faith. His words were kind and true, his heart big and inclusive, and we always felt loved.  We laughed a lot. The words “I love you” were rarely said, but always known. It was a very happy home.  He called many of the football games and I still have the cowbell he’d ring when there was a touchdown. He was the finest of men.

We moved to Dallas/Garland, where I taught the homebound for Richardson ISD and then taught in Garland ISD.  Child 1, Taylor, and child 2, Meredith, were born in Dallas.  In 1986 we moved to our permanent home of Houston, TX, and child 3 (Peyton) was born here.  Taylor and his wife and 2 step-daughters live in Ft. Worth, Meredith lives in Houston and I try hard not to call on her too much, and Peyton and her husband (from Nepal: a nice, peace-loving, husband and father) and their twin boys (my GRANDS!) live in Ft. Worth. All children and GRANDS are Texans.  Sid was director of music ministries and fine arts at FUMC in Garland, then Chapelwood UMC in Houston, and now St. Luke’s UMC in Houston.

Just as we started at St. Luke’s in 1996 Sid was diagnosed with Multiple Sclerosis.  We had much to learn.  Nothing remained the same; everything changed. My first 20 years of marriage had one look and feel; my last 22 years of marriage another.  We all had to work hard.  We had to file some rough edges, jump some rivers, build some bridges, change some expectations, hold hands, forgive, and continue to love one another when it was not easy to do.  (Some of you know exactly what I mean.) Sid is in a wheelchair, still working non-stop (blessing), but independence is a thing of the past. A number of years after the diagnosis my children and I had a great cleansing conversation.  We all said things we wish we’d been able to share earlier, but the timing was just not right.  Boy was that nice! I do have great children! We had to learn how to follow Will Rogers’ wisdom: “Don’t let yesterday use up too much of today.”

I know I am not alone in experiencing all these life/health changes. Some of you are care givers or possibly receivers.  It was not a journey either of us expected to take.  After all, we were young (relatively), healthy, strong, faithful, and kind people.  I don’t believe this was God’s will, it just was.  We have been able to weather this new life setting through strong family support, love for one another, therapy, and a strong faith.

I lost Mom in 2009.  She was my rock with Sid and MS, and with my children throughout everything.  Everything. She was the best! I miss her every day!

I retired from teaching in 2010, having taught +30 years, and I have been working for the Society of Petroleum Engineers ever since.  For 5 years I worked in the training department.  I did no training; I knew absolutely nothing about engineering, oil and gas, NOTHING.  I managed the logistics and learned a whole lot about a world that was completely foreign to me.  I managed classes in Bakersfield, Farmington, Denver, Tulsa, and then got to travel to Amsterdam and Dubai.  Amazing for this Mississippi/Louisiana girl. I have loved it all. When oil and gas took a dive our training department staff went from 6 to 1 and I was fortunate to move within the office to the OTC group.  For the past 3 years I have been the administrator for the Offshore Technology Conference.  Another world of learning.  The logistics for this huge event of 65,000 – 100,000 attendees representing &gt;100 countries, +2000 exhibiting companies from 40 countries, presenting +350 technical papers <em>(I had never even heard of a technical paper) </em>was completely different from the training scene. My learning continued as I took charge of the signage for the show (OMG), the staging guide for all the rooms used throughout the show, the catering for +20 breakfasts and luncheons and feeding the staff and contractors, and for the housing of staff and contractors.  This is a crazy world.  I had no idea that when you attended an event, if there was a trash can in that room, someone had written that down and ordered it.  If you forget to ask for a trashcan, there is not one in the room!  If you order a marker board, do not assume there will be markers or erasers, unless you write that down and order it.  And learning about the $$$$$ … again, OMG.  But it has been quite a ride and I feel so blessed.  So. Blessed.

In 2012 came colon cancer and surgery.  It was caught very early, stage 1, no chemo, fabulous doctors, and now I’m in the survivor’s camp, which is 5 clean years.  Oh my goodness!  Between MS and cancer we remain indebted (on many levels) to the medical center here, Baylor, Methodist &amp; MD Anderson.  That is a fine reason to keep working; the bills and medicines and treatments never stop!  Several of you have experienced cancer or have a loved one with it.  It is mean, but the research community is making huge strides in the field; MS is much the same, but it never goes into remission, there is no surgery to help, and there is much to learn about it.

But I must say, with those grandbabies in Ft. Worth, I’m giving serious thought to permanent retirement.  They fill my heart with joy and delight!  I need to travel!

Thank you, dear friends, for being who you were/are and accepting a preacher’s kid at a very awkward time in her life!  BHS holds very, very, very fond memories for me.

MS can turn on a dime, but at this day and time I plan to be there. I am so looking forward to seeing everyone who is able to get there.

This was too long, but 50 years! (49) Y’all!  That’s a long time!  Ok, I know you know that, I just needed to say it.  Just a few class memories below:

